    value: 《주역》의 태괘(泰卦)로, 서로 화합하여 원만한 상태를 말한다.
english:
  title: Record of Heaven's Opening Grotto
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the second year of Taihe, the year of Renxu, I left my old residence east of the city and moved south to Anshin Village. A cold spring babbles forth from a rocky crevice at the left foot of the grotto. The cave runs deep, the earth lies snug—like a mountain village cottage, clean and pleasing to the eye. I was most content to dwell there, yet the grotto bore an unfortunate name. Even I could not love it.

    Years passed. A white-robed scholar named Ting-gui came to live nearby. His father, the Right Counselor and Hanlin Scholar, would occasionally visit and stay. He often said to me, "The village name is hardly fitting. Why not change it?" I replied, "Long have we called it thus. Not merely this grotto—the whole nation knows it by this name. Even should I rename it, how could I reach every household to make them understand? And who would heed the naming of one so humble as I?" So I left it unchanged until now.

    Yet I have dwelt in this grotto for more than twenty years. Not long after I arrived, I was appointed to the Hanlin Academy and swiftly rose through prestigious offices. Now I have reached the fourth rank. The same fortune befell White Scholar—he too began his career here and advanced through several promotions to become Inspector. Since then, men of high office and generous stipend have flocked to settle here, their attendants crowding the paths. I believe Heaven itself is opening this place.

    When the closed becomes extreme, it transforms to the open. When the blocked endures long, it flows free—such is the eternal principle of yin and yang. As this grotto's fortune turns toward opening, I cannot but give it a new name to answer Heaven's intention. Thus I have named it "Heaven's Opening Grotto." Though men may not yet speak the name I have given, who knows if some future soul might persuade the multitude to call it so? Though men may not speak it, if Heaven understands the meaning behind this naming, the grotto's fortune shall surely flourish. Moreover, men still call the former name "Sealed Grotto"—surely this new name will not fall into disuse.

    Recorded in the eleventh year of Zhenyou, the year of Guiwei.
  footnotes:
    - The I Ching's concepts of "Sealed" (否/Pi) and "Open" (泰/Tai) represent the cycles of obstruction and flourishing that govern both human affairs and natural phenomena.
    - The author's rise from obscurity to high office, and that of his neighbor, seemed to validate his belief that the grotto itself possessed a transformative destiny worthy of a more auspicious name.
